postcontent: Introduced in 2004 and proudly built in the USA, the Mossberg ATR (All-Terrain Rifle) bolt-action has earned the reputation as a dependable, accurate and affordable centerfire rifle with premium features. This .243 Win, rifle features Mossy Oak Break-Up® Infinity™ camouflaged stocks and the “Deer THUGS” logo laser-engraved on the receiver. Honoring the THUGS (Today’s Hunters United for Good) moniker, Mossy Oak donates a portion of the proceeds from their Deer THUGS merchandise sales to the Wounded Warrior Project. At the core of the ATR rifle is an all-steel machined receiver for a positive lock-up and smooth, solid bolt-operation; free-floating, button-rifled fluted barrel with protective recessed muzzle crown, constructed of durable carbon steel; weather-resistant, classic-styled synthetic stock fully camouflaged with Break-Up Infinity; and integral top-loading magazine with five-round total capacity for reliable feeding and ease of loading/unloading. Standard on the ATR Deer THUG rifles, and all ATR models, is Mossberg’s patent-pending, user-adjustable LBA™ (Lightning Bolt Action™) Trigger System. The durable machined trigger assembly is constructed of aircraft-grade aluminum which undergoes a hard-coat anodization to minimize corrosion and wear. The LBA’s unique skeletonized lightning bolt trigger blade blocks the sear from releasing the striker until the blade is fully depressed. This sear engagement design provides for a creep-free trigger. Trigger pull can be adjusted from 2 to 7 pounds with a standard screwdriver. Other value-added features include factory-installed, Weaver-style two-piece scope bases; stock and forend sling swivel studs; and sling. title: For Sale:  1911A1 pistol, Remington, Dulith finish
postcontent: Dulith finish. Serial # 971,896 with NO prefix rather than an underlined No. Although some publications list this serial number as March 1943 production, it may have been finished after production was started again in May-June ’43 (after shutdown in Feb.) with the new on site Ordnance inspector. He designated that new production pistols would have the NO prefix to distinguish newly produced pistols. Since old receivers were used up in new production a mix of NO and No can be found in serial number range 955,000 to 1,016,000. This pistol has the Du-lite finish with some blued parts. Regulations required the same finish on the receiver and slide but parts could be other finishes. Slide is type 2 with markings 1 3/8” long and ending in N.Y.U.S.A. Type 2 slides started about #935,000. Blued High Standard barrel. P stamped on the left side of the lug, HS on the right. Bore is mirror with a little micro erosion from firing. Feed ramp is bright with traces of finish, not polished. Recoil spring plug is blued. Remington narrow hammer. Finely checkered early Remington mainspring cover. Blued checkered slide stop (Colt). Blued safety checkered on top and bottom with no undercut (Colt). Colt supplied these parts to Remington until Remington could make them. Front sight has sloped serrated ramp on rear. Rounded cut on front of rear sight with squared aperture. Early Keyes grips without re-enforcing rings around screws. No hits, bangs or smashed checkering. Bluing on pistol is about 95%. There is some wear on the top of the barrel and on other moving parts. Du-lite was not as sturdy as Parkerizing. Heat treated area on end of the slide is very visible but there is none above the slide stop.
